msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:32
msgid ""
"To that end, the roadmap describes the general goals that we believe the "
"teams ought to be pursuing. These goals were chosen based on a number of "
"sources:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:38
msgid ""
"Preliminary analysis of the [2019 survey](https://blog.rust-lang."
"org/2019/12/03/survey-launch.html), which took place in December."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:40
msgid ""
"The [many #rust2020 blog posts](https://readrust.net/rust-2020/) written in "
"response to our [call for blog posts](https://blog.rust-lang.org/2019/10/29/"
"A-call-for-blogs-2020.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:42
msgid "The thoughts and inputs from the members of the various Rust teams."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:48
msgid ""
"The roadmap is not meant to be \"exclusive\" -- that is, it's not the case "
"that every single thing we do must tie in some way to the roadmap. But we do "
"expect that our largest efforts will be put towards addressing the roadmap "
"goals."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:53
msgid "Structure of the roadmap"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:55
msgid ""
"The roadmap this year is based around a few central themes. These goals are "
"intentionally rather broad -- they are meant to be interpreted throughout "
"the year by the various teams, as they make decisions about what to pursue."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:60
msgid ""
"The roadmap does not contain specific technical details or proposals. We "
"encourage the individual teams to post their thoughts about goals and "
"ongoing projects for 2020, either in the form of [Inside Rust](https://blog."
"rust-lang.org/inside-rust/index.html) blog posts or as [internals](https://"
"internals.rust-lang.org/) threads."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:68
msgid "The goals"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:70
msgid "We have laid out three 'major goals' for Rust in 2020:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:79
msgid "Prepare for a Rust 2021 edition"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:81
msgid ""
"[Editions](https://rust-lang.github.io/rfcs/2052-epochs.html) were "
"established as a means to help communicate the progress of the Rust language "
"and provide a rallying point for overarching pieces of work. One of our "
"goals for this year should be plan out any changes that we wish to make as "
"part of the next Rust edition. If we are to continue the three-year cadence "
"established with the release of Rust 2018, then the next edition would be "
"released in 2021."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:90
msgid ""
"One thing that we learned quite clearly from the experience of Rust 2018 was "
"the importance of preparation. If we wish to do a Rust 2021 edition, we need "
"to be planning for it now. **The goal should be that any changes we wish to "
"make in Rust 2021 are completed by October of 2020**. Completed here means "
"that the changes are available on Nightly. This leaves 2021 to do tooling "
"and polish work, such as lints that will port code forward."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:98
msgid ""
"We have not yet formally decided to do an edition. **One specific scenario "
"where we _would_ expect to go forward with an edition is if we have work "
"landed by October 2020 that relies on one.** The final decision will be made "
"in October with an RFC, and it will be based on the work that has been "
"completed until that date."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:104
msgid ""
"**What might an edition contain?** We've got a number of \"in progress\" "
"language design features that may require minor changes tied to an edition, "
"but this list is by no means exhaustive:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:108
msgid ""
"Error handling, which could potentially see the introduction of new "
"syntactic forms;"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:110
msgid "Improvements to the trait system;"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:111
msgid ""
"Improvements to unsafe code, which might involve introducing new syntax like "
"the `&raw` form proposed in [RFC 2582](https://rust-lang.github.io/rfcs/2582-"
"raw-reference-mir-operator.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:117
msgid ""
"One goal for this year, then, is to flesh out those areas in more detail and "
"decide what changes, if any, we would like to do for Rust 2021. It is key to "
"identify and plan out the changes we want to make sufficiently early that "
"the tooling and documentation around these changes has time to mature before "
"shipping."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:123
msgid ""
"**Editions and our stability promises.** Note that, as ever, issuing a new "
"edition does not mean that old code stops compiling. Furthermore, any "
"edition-related change would require appropriate tooling to help people "
"transition their code, though the tooling might not be completed this year."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:129
msgid ""
"It is notable also that the 2018 edition packaged two \"experiences\" into "
"one: breaking changes and a reflection for the world on the work in the past "
"3 years. That did not go as perfectly as we had hoped, and to this day there "
"remains some confusion on this point. We should, by 2021, identify the "
"marketing strategy we will use for the edition, but this should not affect "
"the choices of breaking changes (as those will always be tied to the edition "
"mechanism). We may, however, choose to decouple the edition from the "
"progress report mechanism. This RFC explicitly does not identify which of "
"these is the better approach to take."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:138
msgid "Follow-through with in-progress designs and efforts"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:140
msgid ""
"I work with Rust for several years. The language is great, the tooling is "
"superb, but I have one growing uneasy feeling too. There are several "
"features that are almost ready, but not there yet. They are in this state "
"for a long time."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:145
msgid "\\-- [vorner](https://vorner.github.io/2019/11/12/rust-2020.html)"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:147
msgid ""
"A major theme highlighted in numerous blog posts and team member's feedback "
"is the tendency for Rust efforts to sometimes \"get stuck\" without being "
"fully completed. Over the years, Rust has accumulated a number of \"almost "
"complete\" efforts -- these range from language/library features to compiler "
"refactorings to community projects."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:154
msgid ""
"One of our goals for this year is to reduce this backlog of \"in progress\" "
"ideas, whether by implementing them or by explicitly opting to reject or "
"postpone the idea. This does not mean that we should not accept any new "
"work, but we should have a high level goal in mind of finishing the year "
"with less, rather than more, \"planned\" work."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:160
msgid ""
"There are several motivations here. First, the set of \"in-progress\" "
"designs and efforts already encompasses the most hotly desired features and "
"initiatives. But further, stalled work can be demotivating and confusing. "
"When an initiative spans over several years, it becomes harder and harder to "
"track the current state and to remember all of the key design constraints. "
"This in turn hinders participation in the Rust project and makes it harder "
"to figure out what is going on (see also: the goal of improving visibility "
"into the state of our initiatives and design efforts)."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:170
msgid "Improve project functioning, governance, and visibility"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:172
msgid ""
"Organizational work is at the core of everything else that happens in the "
"project, and above all else this seems to be the one thing we should keep "
"improving. We’re growing fast, and our organization needs to grow with it."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:174
msgid "\\-- [Yoshua Wuyts](https://blog.yoshuawuyts.com/rust-2020/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:176
msgid ""
"The Rust project has grown dramatically over the last few years, in every "
"dimension:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:178
msgid "We have more users than ever before."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:179
msgid ""
"We are seeing many more companies -- and much larger companies -- adopting "
"Rust."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:180
msgid "Our organization and Rust teams have grown."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:182
msgid ""
"This is great news! But with this growth comes challenges.  We are finding "
"that it is harder and harder to ensure communication across the "
"organization. It can often be challenging to find enough people to do the "
"work we would like to get done, which in turn leads to burnout or people "
"leaving the project. We've identified three major goals that we think will "
"help."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:191
msgid ""
"Right now it is very difficult to answer questions like \"what are the "
"active efforts and how can I help\" to \"what is the status of feature X\". "
"This is true both for folks who are deeply embedded in the Rust organization "
"and for newcomers."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:196
msgid ""
"There are many ways to improve visibility, but the most basic step is simply "
"expending more effort on posting updates and documenting the status.  Things "
"like the Inside Rust blog are helpful here, and we should look for other "
"ways to incorporate lightweight status updates into our workflows."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:202
msgid ""
"There are a number of possible sources for this information today, such as "
"feature gate labels and tracking implementation history in tracking issues. "
"Most of these have not been formally introduced to all teams nor have they "
"been described in any particular nature; this experimentation has yielded "
"mostly positive results. However, it does not do a good job of targeting end-"
"users who have never visited the Rust issue tracker. We want to actively "
"target community members who are not actively involved in the teams. In "
"doing so, we should also avoid increasing the busywork factor on teams."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:211
msgid ""
"It has been noted by multiple team members that even those who are _very_ "
"involved in the project (core team members, for example) frequently note "
"that they also do not have a good sense of the current project goals and "
"priorities. So we are also not meeting the needs for team members to stay up "
"to date with current initiatives."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:217
msgid ""
"There is clearly room to innovate on both fronts, and existing "
"experimentation should also not be overlooked."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:222
msgid ""
"One common challenge for us is that we seem to lack enough people to get the "
"work done that we would like to get done. But what we're missing is not just "
"_any_ people, it's people who can help to do the \"leadership\" work that "
"knits the project together."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:227
msgid ""
"This work takes many forms. Sometimes it is technical, such as writing "
"mentoring instructions on issues, but more often it is organizational, such "
"as running meetings, posting blog posts (see the previous point), or making "
"plans."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:232
msgid ""
"We have made great progress over the years by intentionally focusing on the "
"\"on-ramp\" to contribution, through efforts like tagging E-easy issues. "
"We've made more limited progress on helping people \"step up\" towards "
"leadership roles."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:237
msgid ""
"Part of the problem here is money. One of the biggest challenges around "
"organizational work is that it is quite demanding in terms of time. It "
"requires availability. It is difficult to do in your spare time. Therefore, "
"helping to ensure that it is easier for people to get paid for their work on "
"Rust -- and especially their **organizational** work -- is one way we might "
"make progress here."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:244
msgid ""
"However, it's worth emphasizing that this doesn't necessarily mean people "
"whose job description is _solely_ to work on Rust. There are many companies "
"using Rust, and many of them would like to help out, but we need to do "
"better at harnessing and directing those efforts. As Parity put it in their "
"#rust2020 post:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:250
msgid ""
"“We, too, have team members who are interested in helping on specialization "
"or fixing the aforementioned bugs. However, it’s often unclear whether the "
"work is worthwhile. To a business, it is hard to argue that one might spend "
"a month or two working on a new feature without any assurance that the "
"approach taken would be accepted.”"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:257
msgid ""
"\\-- [Benjamin Kampmann, speaking for Parity](https://www.parity.io/"
"rust-2020/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:261
msgid ""
"An RFC, or \"request for comments\" is a mechanism by which a group of "
"people can get feedback from a wider community on proposed changes. The idea "
"is that a written proposal outlines a change's scope, implementation "
"details, rationale and impact on the ecosystem, then people make comments on "
"the proposal. Usually by the time that everybody has stopped shouting at "
"each other, the RFC is ready to be merged, meaning it is accepted and its "
"vision can be implemented. This can either be implementing a feature, or "
"removing unstable flags from it."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:271
msgid ""
"\\-- [spacekookie](https://spacekookie.de/blog/rust-2020-the-rfc-process-and-"
"distributions/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:273
msgid ""
"The RFC process has been a crucial part of Rust's organization for a long "
"time. The process of documenting and talking over our designs is often very "
"helpful for improving the design and sometimes leads to dramatic changes. "
"Many other languages have adopted RFCs and explicitly cited Rust as "
"precedent."
msgstr ""

#: src/2857-roadmap-2020.md:279
msgid ""
"Of course, we also have ample evidence that the RFC process as presently "
"practiced does not work well for larger-scale or controversial designs. Last "
"year we put a lot of energy into thinking about techniques for improving the "
"process, and this year we need to put more of that energy into actually "
"making those changes."
msgstr ""

